The paper proposes a method for cross-modal hashing, which involves learning effective hashing codes from weakly-paired data. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and information retrieval (cs.IR) sub-categories, as these are the areas where cross-modal retrieval is commonly studied. Additionally, the paper mentions that hashing has been widely adopted for large-scale data retrieval in many domains, which suggests that it could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. Finally, the paper proposes a clustering-based matching strategy and a hashing quantitative loss, which suggests that it could also belong to the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category.
